Authors: Toye Adebayo (aadeb02) and Valens Dabagire (vdabag01).

This project implements the 40image program for the image format. 
The program supports two modes: compress (-c) and decompress (-d). 
It reads input from a filename if one is provided, otherwise it 
reads from standard input, and it writes all output to standard output.

The main entry point is 40image.c, which handles the command-line 
arguments and then calls either compress40 or decompress40. The 
core compression/decompression pipeline is implemented in compress40.c 
/ compress40.h. Compression trims images with odd dimensions to an 
even width/height, converts each pixel from RGB to component video 
(YPbPr), processes the image in 2x2 blocks, applies the discrete 
cosine transform (DCT) to the four Y values, quantizes the coefficients, 
quantizes the average chroma values using the provided arith40 functions, 
packs everything into a 32-bit codeword using Bitpack, and writes 
each codeword in big-endian byte order with the required header. 
Decompression reads and checks the header, reads codewords in 
big-endian order, unpacks the fields, dequantizes, runs the inverse DCT, 
converts the resulting YPbPr values back to RGB, clamps values to 
valid ranges, stores pixels into the output array, and finally 
writes a PPM image.

The math and conversion helpers are split into separate modules. 
pixel_conversion.c / pixel_conversion.h handles RGB to YPbPr conversion, 
quantization/unquantization for the small DCT coefficients (b, c, d), 
and clamps RGB values before scaling to the output denominator. dct.c / 
dct.h implements the 2x2 DCT and inverse DCT. bitpack.c implements 
the Bitpack interface, including fit checks, field extraction, and 
field insertion, and it raises Bitpack_Overflow when values do not 
fit in the requested bit width. The project also uses uarray2.c/h 
and uarray2b.c for 2D array support used by the A2Methods blocked 
array interface.

We discussed the assignment and testing approach with classmates at a 
high level, but we did not copy code from other students. We used 
course-provided libraries and interfaces, including arith40, pnm, 
and a2methods.

All required parts of the assignment are implemented.

We spent approximately 5 hours on analysis and design, and approximately 
30 hours on implementation, debugging, and testing.